<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-27T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-27T02:00:00-05:00" n="655" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/469: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-27T15:00:00+08:00">January 27, 1938—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 27—12:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>152. Reference my No. 140, January 26, 1 p.m. British Chargé dAffaires
                            informs me today that the telegram from the Inspector General to the
                            Minister of Finance has now gone forward. He has not stated whether he
                            is indorsing the proposal. Repeated to Hankow, Peiping and Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>